      <name>Intelligence Summary</name>
      <Placemark>
        <name>AI Council Assessment</name>
        <styleUrl>#intel</styleUrl>
        <description>The synthesized intelligence reveals a US military posture characterized by sustained global operations and high operational tempo, with carrier strike groups and amphibious ready groups deployed or transiting key theaters. USS Gerald R. Ford (CVN-78) is actively transiting the Eastern Mediterranean after a port visit in Split, Croatia, indicating continued NATO engagement and regional presence. USS George H.W. Bush (CVN-77) remains in-port at Norfolk, preparing for deployment, suggesting a rotation cycle to maintain carrier availability. Amphibious readiness is highlighted by USS Rushmore&#39;s transit through the Strait of Malacca, reinforcing US Central Command operations and Indo-Pacific posture. Strategic airlift remains a critical enabler, with multiple C-17s and other transports engaged in rapid deployment, resupply, and high-priority missions, including VIP and special operations support. ISR and maritime patrol activity is concentrated along European and Middle Eastern coastlines, with fixed-wing and rotary-wing assets conducting surveillance and reconnaissance. The presence of JANET-operated aircraft underscores sensitive logistics and communications support. Overall, the data reflects a US military maintaining robust global readiness amid evolving geopolitical tensions, with a focus on deterrence, power projection, and rapid response capabilities across multiple theaters.</description>
